
[1]tent

   TENT, n. [L. tentorium, from tendo, to stretch.]

   1. A pavilion or portable lodge consisting of canvas or other coarse
   cloth, stretched and sustained by poles; used for sheltering persons
   from the weather, particularly soldiers in camp. The wandering Arabs
   and Tartars lodge in tents. The Israelites lodged in tents forty years,
   while they were in the desert.

   2. In surgery, a roll of lint or linen, used to dilate an opening in
   the flesh, or to prevent the healing of an opening from which matter or
   other fluid is discharged.

   TENT, n. [L. tinctus.] A kind of wine of a deep red color, chiefly from
                         Galicia or Malaga in Spain.

              TENT, v.i. To lodge as in a tent; to tabernacle.

     TENT, v.t. To probe; to search as with a tent; as, to tent a wound.

   I'll tent him to the quick.

   1. To keep open with a tent.
